# MVNO Cell Service

> Concept for a Mobile Virtual Network Operator - reselling cellular service with a unique angle.

---

## Overview

An **MVNO (Mobile Virtual Network Operator)** is a wireless carrier that doesn't own network infrastructure but instead purchases wholesale access from major carriers (Verizon, AT&T, T-Mobile) and resells it under their own brand.

**Status:** Very early concept. Needs significant research and validation before serious consideration.

---

## What is an MVNO?

### How It Works
```
Major Carrier (MNO)          MVNO              Customer
[Verizon/AT&T/T-Mobile] --> [Your Brand] --> [End Users]
     Owns towers              Resells           Pays you
     Wholesale rates          Retail rates
```

### Examples of MVNOs
| MVNO | Underlying Network | Angle |
|------|--------------------|-------|
| Mint Mobile | T-Mobile | Budget/prepaid |
| Visible | Verizon | Unlimited simplicity |
| Cricket | AT&T | Value tier |
| Google Fi | T-Mobile + US Cellular | Smart switching |
| Ting | T-Mobile/Verizon | Pay for what you use |
| Republic Wireless | T-Mobile | WiFi-first |

---

## Why Consider This?

### Potential Opportunities
1. **Underserved niches:** Specific demographics or use cases
2. **Brand loyalty:** If existing ventures build audience
3. **Recurring revenue:** Subscription model
4. **Tech differentiation:** App/service layer innovation

### Market Reality
- MVNO market is **highly competitive**
- Margins are **thin** (wholesale costs are significant)
- Customer acquisition is **expensive**
- Churn is **high** (people switch carriers easily)

